ol.li:
Since R is in reduced row echelon form, we must have

    d=\vec{4 0 0}

The other two vectors provide special solutions for R, showing that R has a rank of 1: again, since it is in reduced row echelon form, the bottom two rows must be all 0, and top row is (1 -2 -5), i.e., 
R=\mat{
    1 -2 -5;
    0 0 0;
    0 0 0
    }

The matrix connecting R and d to the original A and b is
E = E_{31}E_{21} = \mat{
     1 0 0;
     0 1 0;
    -5 0 1
    } \cdot \mat{
    1 0 0;
    -3 1 0;
    0 0 1
    } = \mat{
    1 0 0;
    -3 1 0;
    -5 1 0
    }
That is, R=EA and Eb=d.Thus A=E\inv R and b=E\inv d, giving 
A = \mat{
     1 0 0;
     3 1 0;
     5 0 1
    } \cdot \mat{
    1 -2 -5;
    0 0 0;
    0 0 0
    } = \mat{
    1 -2 -5;
    3 -6 -15;
    5 -10 -25
    }
b=\mat{
    1 0 0;
    3 1 0;
    5 0 1
    } \cdot \mat{
    4;
    0;
    0
    }=\mat{
    4;
    12;
    20
    }
